title: In support of: Food-additive titanium dioxide targets intestinal lysomac immune cells
description:
Data, image analysis pipelines and code as described in the publication entitled: "Food-additive titanium dioxide targets intestinal lysomac immune cells".

ABSTRACT
Food-grade titanium dioxide is a globally-important, persistent particle with demonstrable cell adjuvant activity and a growing halo of controversy in terms of potential genotoxicity. And yet, critical information on absorption and cell exposure is unknown. Here we show, in human tissues, that the biologically-active apical region of small intestinal lymphoid follicles (Peyer’s patches) accumulates titanium dioxide particles. We entirely recapitulate this finding in a murine model and demonstrate correlative mouse-human dosimetry via quantitative image analysis of cells and vesicles with single-particle detection. Epithelial microfold cells funnel particles into a single macrophage phenotype (lysomacs), with uptake that is many orders of magnitude greater than elsewhere. The work provides the precise in vivo target and correct dosimetry to address outstanding questions regarding biological impact. Peyer’s patches orchestrate antibody responses to luminal antigens and this is now occurring in an environment of manmade particulate adjuvants that we have not co-evolved with.
